4ebba272-2445-414f-bcab-91baca307aa3	Maslow Level: Self-Actualization Needs\n\nSub-Category: The Empty Nest and Reclaiming Shared Purpose\n\nRelated Survey Variables: Number of Children (Transitioning out of home) / Happiness\n\nPsychological Context: When children finally leave the home, couples often face a profound existential crisis. The shared project of raising children is over. If they haven't maintained their connection, they are left looking at a stranger. This is a Self-Actualization challenge: "Who are we now, and what is our purpose for the next 30 years?"\n\nCounseling Framework & Diagnosis: If an older couple (or a couple with adult children) reports feeling empty, bored, or disconnected without active conflict, they are struggling to transition into the next phase of life. They need a new shared vision.\n\nActionable Advice for the AI to Provide: 1. Grieve the Transition: Acknowledge that it is entirely normal to feel a sense of grief and profound loss when children leave, even if it is a successful milestone. 2. Rediscover the Individual: Before connecting as a couple, encourage both partners to ask themselves what hobbies, passions, or self-actualization goals they put on hold for the last two decades. 3. Build the "Next Chapter" Vision: Advise the couple to brainstorm a new shared purpose. This could involve traveling, volunteering, mentoring, or simply restructuring their daily lives to maximize joy and companionship.	{"source": "c:\\\\Users\\\\User\\\\OneDrive\\\\Documents\\\\GitHub\\\\AI-Chatbot-for-Marriage-Counseling\\\\3-ai-service-python\\\\RAG_Knowledge_Base\\\\level5_actualization_empty_nest.md"}	[0.0054844273,-0.0031683845,-0.045489695,0.026917003,-0.013604429,-0.07793242,-0.017201737,0.026773557,0.009336749,-0.008689927,-0.021890992,-0.030752555,0.009291527,-0.008453181,-0.004473873,-0.011410807,-0.051753722,0.016917916,-0.03565935,0.016349226,-0.0031369403,0.03103457,-0.030173982,0.015886405,0.022266366,0.037324272,0.0035155558,0.015246